{{Orphan|date=April 2013}}

Dr. '''Eric L. Ding''' (born 1983 in [[Shanghai]]) is an American [[nutritionist]] and [[epidemiologist]], a faculty at [[Harvard School of Public Health]], Executive Director of the ''Campaign for Cancer Prevention'',<ref>[http://www.causes.com/cancer Campaign for Cancer Prevention]</ref> Director of Epidemiology with Microclinic International, a [[WEF]] Global Shaper, and a Soros Fellow.<ref>[http://www.pdsoros.org/ Paul and Daisy Soros Foundation]</ref> 

Ding founded the ''Campaign for Cancer Prevention'', currently with over 6 million members on [[Causes (company)|Causes]], to accelerate medical research.<ref>[http://well.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/12/08/a-web-campaign-for-cancer-prevention/ A Web Campaign for Cancer Prevention. December 8, 2011]</ref> He was recognized in the [[New York Times]]<ref>[http://www.nytimes.com/2006/09/13/health/13vioxx.html New York Times. Studies Find Higher Rates of Heart Risk With Vioxx. September 13, 2006]</ref> and [[USA Today]] as a whistle-blower in the [[Vioxx]] drug safety controversy. He also writes as an op-ed contributor for [[The Huffington Post]].<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/eric-ding-phd Eric Ding on Huffington Post]</ref>

==Early life and education==

Ding was born in Shanghai, China, and was raised in the United States. He is an alum of the Pennsylvania Governor's School for Health Care.<ref>[http://www.pennlive.com/news/patriotnews/index.ssf?/base/news/1235105738167040.xml&coll=1 Pennsylvania Governor's School]</ref> As a child, doctors discovered that he had developed a baseball-size tumor in his chest. His initial prognosis was for less than 5 years life,<ref>[http://www.bu.edu/bostonia/fall08/ding/ Bostonia, Fall 2008]</ref><ref>[http://well.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/12/08/a-web-campaign-for-cancer-prevention/ A Web Campaign for Cancer Prevention. December 8, 2011]</ref> but he survived.

Ding attended [[The Johns Hopkins University]], graduating with Honors in Public Health and ''[[Phi Beta Kappa]]''. He earned his dual doctorate in epidemiology, doctorate in nutrition, and doctoral minor in biostatistics, from [[Harvard]] at age 23. He then completed his postdoctoral fellowship in Nutrition at the [[Harvard School of Public Health]]. At Harvard, he also received the [[Derek Bok]] Distinction in Teaching Award from [[Harvard College]]. He once attended [[Boston University]] School of Medicine, but did not receive a degree.<ref>http://www.bu.edu/bostonia/fall08/ding/</ref>

==Work==

Ding's research focuses on obesity and nutritional risk factors for diabetes, heart disease, and cancer - with focus on translational approaches for health communication, prevention, social networks on health, and social media technology for health. His expertise also includes evidence-based medicine, and global disease burden and policy. He has published major reports, including in the [[New England Journal of Medicine]], [[Journal of the American Medical Association]], [[PLoS Medicine]], [[The Lancet]], which together have received over 1900 citations.

Ding is a Fellow of the Paul and Daisy Soros Foundation,<ref>[http://www.pdsoros.org/current_fellows/index.cfm/yr/2008#ding Soros Fellow: Eric Ding]</ref> and as chief corresponding author of a JAMA report, recognized for his role as a whistle-blower of the controversial drug safety of [[Vioxx]] and other [[COX-2 inhibitor]]s, he was recognized and named in the [[New York Times]] and [[USA Today]]. 

He has also served as advisor for the World Health Organization and the EU European Commission, as judge for the annual VH1 Do Something Awards, and was an appointed member of the [[World Health Organization]]-sponsored Global Burden of Disease Project.<ref>[http://www.globalburden.org/ Global Burden of Disease Project]</ref> His work has been cited by directors of CDC and CMMS in the framework of the federal "Million Hearts" Initiative.<ref>[http://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMp1110421 The “Million Hearts” Initiative — Preventing Heart Attacks and Strokes. Thomas R. Frieden and Donald M. Berwick. N Engl J Med 2011; 365:e27]</ref> He has consulted for the WHO and the [[European Commission]]. He also serves as Director of Epidemiology of Microclinic International,<ref>[http://www.microclinics.org/ MicroClinic International]</ref> as principal investigator of several intervention programs for obesity and diabetes prevention. 

Having survived a childhood battle with a baseball-sized tumor, Ding founded the Campaign for Cancer Prevention, and was featured in [[Newsweek]],<ref>[http://www.newsweek.com/id/62168 Newsweek, October 2007]</ref> the [[New York Times]],<ref>[http://well.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/12/08/a-web-campaign-for-cancer-prevention/ A Web Campaign for Cancer Prevention. December 11, 2011]</ref> and on 40 million bags of [[Doritos]], sponsored by [[Do Something]]. He is also known for developing a direct-to-science model for accelerating cancer research,<ref>[http://exchange.causes.com/2010/12/campaign-for-cancer-prevention/ Campaign for Cancer Prevention: The Cause to Find the Cancer Causes - Direct Funding for Cancer Research from Crowd-Sourcing Millions on Causes]</ref> and advocate of crowdfunding for medical research.<ref>[http://well.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/12/08/a-web-campaign-for-cancer-prevention/ A Web Campaign for Cancer Prevention. December 8, 2011]</ref> To date, his efforts have raised over $500,000 in public donations for innovative cancer research, and directs several cancer prevention advocacy platforms totaling over 17 million members.

A former keynote presenter at [[AtGoogleTalks|Google TechTalk]], he been featured in [[Google]] Research<ref>[http://research.google.com/video.html Google Research]</ref> for development of a 130-year cohort study of [[Major League Baseball]] to study obesity and mortality. Ding's work has been mentioned in books, including ''CauseWired''<ref>[http://www.amazon.com/dp/0470375043 CauseWired by Watson, Wiley & Sons, Inc 2008]</ref> by [[Tom Watson (journalist)|Tom Watson]], and ''Zilch: The Power of Zero in Business''<ref>[http://www.amazon.com/dp/1591843146 Zilch by Lublin, Portfolio, Penguin Group USA 2010]</ref> by [[Nancy Lublin]], and ''Shift & Reset: Strategies for Addressing Serious Issues in a Connected Society''<ref>[http://www.amazon.com/Shift-Reset-Strategies-Addressing-Connected/dp/0470942673 Shift and Reset: Strategies for Addressing Serious Issues in a Connected Society by Reich, Wiley 2011]</ref> by Brian Reich. 

He was recognized by [[Craig Newmark]] as among “16 People and Organizations Changing the World in 2012”. He also received the 2012 Outstanding Young Leader Award from the Boston Chamber of Commerce.<ref>[http://bostonchamber.com/networking-and-events/past-events/ten-outstanding-young-leaders/2012-toyl-honorees/ Ten Outstanding Young Leaders Award]</ref> He formerly served on the Board of Advisors for [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]'s [[Raising Malawi]] Foundation.<ref>[http://www.raisingmalawi.org/blog/entry/dr.-eric-ding-joins-raising-malawi/ Dr. Eric Ding Joins Raising Malawi]</ref>

